5/ ...then I know I am dealing with someone who doesn't understand that minority groups have histories of oppression that require that they be treated differently in order to be treated fairly and equally. Sorry to go on so long, I hope I'm making a bit of sense. :-) Mel

4/ The longer quote is from the same book, but I haven't located the p. #. I meant it in relation to individuality, but people have used it in other ways (e.g. re special ed). I'm not sure it can apply to groups, but if I hear the words color-blind" and "post-racial society"..."

3/ Another version: “Children are born as individuals. If we fail to see that, if we see them as clay to be molded in any shape we like, the tougher ones will fight back and end up spiteful and wild, while the less strong will lose that uniqueness they were born with.” (more...)

2/ I started saying this to parents to emphasize that their kids come into the world already different, and it may seem like treating them exactly the same is equal treatment, but it might not address their needs. The quote has been used in various ways https://www.google.com/search?client=safari&rls=en&sxsrf=ALeKk01sSQTI2ahdrg6s2bV9AgoFIdalUg%3A1593192883531&ei=szH2Xu7lH9S6tAbE35vwAw&q=%E2%80%9CIn+order+to+be+treated+fairly+and+equally%2C+chidren+have+to+be+treated+differently.%E2%80%9D&oq=%E2%80%9CIn+order+to+be+treated+fairly+and+equally%2C+chidren+have+to+be+treated+differently.%E2%80%9D&gs_lcp=CgZwc3ktYWIQDFAAWABgj4kyaABwAHgAgAEAiAEAkgEAmAEAqgEHZ3dzLXdpeg&sclient=psy-ab&ved=0ahUKEwiui4b_gaDqAhVUHc0KHcTvBj4Q4dUDCAs …

1/ Hi Sanford, being a nerd I had to track down the exact quote, which is, “In order to be treated fairly and equally, children have to be treated differently.” It appeared on p. 405 of my 1991 book *Childhood: A Multicultural View*, companion to a PBS series (more to come...)

# AACR20 Enticing correlative data with evidence of T-cell responses noted: cytokine induction, ex vivo responses noted by ELISPOT in 73%, generating both CD4 and CD8 responses, and RO-457 stimulated T-cells identified in the tumor. # OncoAlertpic.twitter.com/ZawunPVwo8

# AACR20 This was largely safety/feasibility as it included many tumors not typically responsive to IO therapy, most PDL1 low/negative. Safety comparable to atezo monotherapy overall. # OncoAlertpic.twitter.com/2vwpNB72Mw

# AACR20 The neoantigens are processed to peptides and presented on MHC-I and MHC-II molecules, leading to activation of both CD4 and CD8 neoantigen specific T cells. 8 doses given weekly/bi-weekly then as maintenance with atezo given q21d. # OncoAlertpic.twitter.com/gRDq0PQgI7

# AACR20 RO-457 given IV, delivered to APCs, binds TLR7/8, activates dendritic cells, generates proinflammatory cytokines, upregulates costimulatory molecules and induces translation of RO-457 into polypeptide with neoantigens. # OncoAlertpic.twitter.com/gqKVs9dPtk

# AACR20 iNeST RO-457 is generated for an individual patient. Biopsy subject to NGS and bioinformatics used to predict neoantigens. Neoantigens encoded on two mRNA molecules (each with up to 10 neoantigens) and packaged in lipoplex nanoparticle formulation. # OncoAlertpic.twitter.com/h0SQOfYGVm

# AACR20 TMB holds some value but it is likely a surrogate for neoantigen load, which may be the more important predictor. The challenge is that neoantigens are not shared between patients. iNeST is designed to expand neoantigen-specific T-cells in a specific patient. # OncoAlertpic.twitter.com/Khn1DZUCft

# AACR20 Clinical plenary highlights the phase Ib study of RO7198457, an individualized neoantigen specific immunotherapy (iNeST) with atezolizumab. This represents a personalized immunotherapy approach that designs the agent based on likely neoantigens. # OncoAlertpic.twitter.com/FRGHFmp7Q0
